article.headline: Los Angeles 83, San Antonio 70
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- After the Los Angeles Sparks wrapped up first
place in the Western Conference for the fourth straight year, Lisa
Leslie put the celebration on hold.

"It's very special to win the conference, but I think it's hard
to celebrate about it because we're not done with what our major
goal is -- to win a championship," Leslie said. "It's great and we
have pride in it, but we have no banner saying we're conference
champions because we want the championship banner."

Leslie scored a season-high 31 points in an 83-70 win over the
San Antonio Silver Stars on Saturday.

Mwadi Mabika added 16 points and Nikki Teasley 13 for the Sparks
(23-10) before a Staples Center crowd that included Los Angeles
Lakers center Shaquille O'Neal.

Los Angeles has won four in a row since Leslie returned from the
knee injury that sidelined her for 11 games after the WNBA All-Star
game on July 12.

The victory came a day after Sparks center Rhonda Mapp became
the first player dismissed from the league for violating its
anti-drug program, the latest jolt to the two-time defending
champions.

"This has been a year of adversity for the Sparks," Leslie
said. "It has been very draining at times. It has not been easy,
but to raise that banner and win a championship will make it all
that much sweeter."

Mapp, who was in her sixth season, cannot apply for
reinstatement for at least two years, according to league rules.

This season, Los Angeles endured injuries to All-Stars Leslie
and DeLisha Milton, and waived Latasha Byears in June, reportedly
amid a probe into an alleged sexual assault on a former teammate.

Margo Dydek matched a career high with 27 points, and Marie
Ferdinand and Adrienne Goodson had 16 each for the Silver Stars,
who concluded their inaugural season in San Antonio after moving
from Utah. They finished 12-22, sixth in the seven-team Western
Conference.

"I think we need to work on coming together as a team so that
next year we can be a contender for the playoffs," Goodson said.
"We also need to find a team chemistry that will put us back into
contention."

The Sparks were up 45-34 at halftime and twice led by 14. The
Silver Stars scored six consecutive points to cut the deficit to
63-57 with 6:38 to play, but Los Angeles responded with seven
unanswered points.

San Antonio scored the game's first six points, but the Sparks
took the lead for good midway through the first half as Mabika,
Jennifer Gillom and Teasley hit consecutive 3-pointers.

A 14-2 run put Los Angeles ahead 40-27 with 4:26 left in the
half.
